segments.text: At NETCOG, N-C-T-C-O-G, in addition to what we've just mentioned, I was instrumental in starting the water planning, and the way it worked out was that the initial staff that was there, the nucleus of three years.
What program, what federal agency was that?
Well, at that time it was the predecessor of EPA, Water Resources Council or something like that.
They hadn't established EPA yet, and it was a federated program and dealt with
with the regional planning of wastewater and water supply, that kind of thing, but primarily wastewater.
And so the Upper Trinity River study began with my being the staff coordinator for it before a water director was hired.
And then when the program got going, a water director was hired, and the thing moved into his hands.
The same thing happened with a number of other programs.
For example, Dan Petty, who was the director
director of administration for the office, helped to establish the police academy there.
Then when a police academy director was hired, that was all given to him.
And I started the first work on the A95 review program when it was initiated.
And then a director of regional services was appointed, and he took that over.
In fact, I think that Dan was the guy that took it over, but I was in on the first part of it.
A lot of it was, you might say, getting the ball rolling and never following through on very many things.
And we also started the population estimating program that now is an annual event at Cogginby.
It's a very important part.
This is one of the things that Bill Pitstick was very interested in and thought was very important.
I think he was very right in his
estimation about that, and it's a very important and a really reasonably accurate estimation program being within 3% of the 1980 census for most cities in the area.

Another thing that we did which stands alone in some respects, and this involves another one of the people you're going to interview, Mike Mahoney, is that sometime in somewhere between 73 and 75, I believe, maybe 72, we decided that
A lot of cities in our region needed a lot of planning help, and that they needed some models.
And when I say we, this was a special committee under the A95 review system.
I sort of grew up with planners and engineers and some city managers on there.
And they said, we need to have some models for local development ordinances.
And so we developed a committee, and our staff developed
an outline of what we wanted, solicited proposals from consultants.

And Mike Mahoney, who had been director of planning in Fort Worth, was now consulting, won the award and developed what was called the Model Land Development Code, number one, and number two, the Community Planning Manual series.
And the first, I can provide you with a little description of that for your appendix, essentially what the development code was.

was a combination of zoning ordinance and subdivision regulations, floodplain regulations, and what do you call it, trailer home, mobile home park kind of regulations, and special district, industrial parks, apartment buildings, and shopping center regulations, that kind of thing.
Did this come about about the same time as the ALI model ended up in court?
This preceded it.
And incidentally, I was very surprised to see that I had been one of the first persons
in all modesty, I say, is to be invited by Charlie Haar way back in the mid-'70s when they were starting work on this thing.
No, it was the mid-'60s, mid-'60s, because it was a 10-year project which ended around 75, 76.
And Charlie Haar was with the HHFA at that time in Washington.
And he'd invited, I don't know, about 20 of us, planners, to come in.
And because of my work in Tulsa and
Broadly because of that reputation, I was invited to take part in that.
And I still have those old files of the first drafts and the original meeting that was held on that thing.
Anyways, this was separate.
But the idea of a development code which combined and simply combined subdivision and zoning ordinances into one code was actually evident in this model and development code.
And maybe we didn't call it quite that.
Maybe it was model community development or something like that.
I can give you this complete description of it.
And Mike was the guy that did it.
He can tell you more about it.

Then the other thing that happened there at COG that I think I would take some pride in, because this is the one thing that's cited in all works about planning in Texas, is this COG series of 10 small manuals, each about 3 eighths to a half an inch thick.
And they want to update that now.
And hopefully, we can help them through the APA to do that.

Anyways, the other activity that led, in a sense, to my leaving the COG was that in about 1975, we were invited by the Institute of Urban Studies at UT Arlington to express interest or to evaluate a training program that they had come upon by virtue of being involved in a multi-state
Title I Higher Education Act kind of study of training for local government people and so forth in which they did something in some other state.
It happens that St. John's University in St.
Cloud, Minnesota was the one that had developed for the state planning office there a series of training packages for local officials.
And they were small little workshops of three hours each, one on zoning, one on subdivision regulation, et cetera.
They had developed about six of those.
And they were providing them as a part of this bigger interstate study and said, what we'll do is we'll say, OK, you take these packages, you see if they're applicable in your state, and then you
Try them out, and use them for training.
And we'll do the same.
We'll take what you've developed, and we'll try it out in our area.
But what happened was, with some way or another, they were able to hire Doug Crear and P.D.
Crear, Jr. And he came on the staff, and he took the zoning module that they had and adapted it to Texas zoning law and revised the slideshow and so forth.
And then when they got that all done, they had about, let's say, three or four others that were really worthy
They asked me, what do I think of it?
I said, the only way I can tell you that is to try it out.
And so we indeed tried it.
And in 1975, in August, I believe, we had our first trial in Euless, Texas.
And we invited several cities from around there to send people.
And it was a Friday and a Saturday.
We had four modules, three hours in the morning, three hours in the afternoon.
And that led, on my part, to, in the next few years,
to conducting about 12 of these two-day workshops all over north central Texas.
And I became interested in doing that, and did that almost exclusively, and then made a transition from working at COG to working at UT Arlington in the Institute of Urban Studies.
And there was an intermediate period there where I was actually under contract to the COG to continue to conduct some of those workshops for them on a more or less quarterly basis.

And when I got to UT Arlington, because of that experience, we decided, or they decided, the dean and so forth decided to get into another federally-aided program that involved us with the Texas Municipal League and with the similar leagues in the four adjoining states.
on a similar kind of program to try out providing the leads with the capacity to train their people.
Well, we had a very successful project insofar as the quality of training and the reactions of the training.
But it turned out that they really needed professional planners interested in training and delivering the thing to make it work.
In other words, they needed something like the short course
or a modified form of it, which is what these workshops were, a modified form.
And that one thing led to another so that eventually we had some three federated programs that involved different groups.

We finally even worked with the Texas Department of Community Affairs on preparing some extra planning so that the original six modules, which the Institute of Urban Studies obtained in 1975 as being a part of this project, now numbers some 30 modules.
that I can also provide you with the short titles of all those, running almost the full range.
And as an example, instead of running just four workshops a year, in the next month, I'll be running five or six workshops.
parties to five or six workshops, because others are involved as well.
We try to do it that way now.
And these do not, incidentally, as was feared initially by some of the people on the educational foundation, these do not take the place of what they complement and supplement the short course.
And indeed, the educational foundation is now looking toward trying to establish these
more strongly with each of the COGs, if possible, or at least each of the APA sections in the state so that there will be educational foundation support for regionalized training.

In a sense, a mini short course that can be regionalized and closely correlated with the annual short course that started in 1971, as we said, and will become part of an integrated program of training for local officials.

At UT Arlington, the printing program in planning, called the City and Regional Planning Program, was initiated at the same time that the School of Architecture and Environmental Design was established.
And the exact date of that, I can't be sure, but it was sometime around 1970, if I remember correctly.
Or maybe it was mid-'70s.
Anyway, that is a matter of record.
We can dig that out to be sure about it.

But Harold Box, who was a prominent architect, member of the firm of Pratt, Box, and Whitney in Dallas, was apparently invited by the university or some way to become the first dean, and he established the school.
And he included in that
architecture, landscape architecture, environmental design, and building construction, and urban and regional planning, about a five-pronged total program.
And I guess maybe eventually interior design came in or something too in that whole thing.
And the man that he hired as the first director was Joe B. Goldstein, AICP.
who can probably add some to this about the early history of it.
Anyways, initially, it was under the auspices of that Architectural and Environmental Design.
And then about two years ago, moved over to the Institute of Urban Studies since it became very much more closely associated with local government concerns, which was part of the Institute's purview.
And the, what shall I say, the program
was the third in Texas, and was the third recognized program in Texas.
And I don't recall right now, but I know that the North Central Texas section of the AIP volunteered to Hal Box to help design a curriculum.
And the chairperson of that committee was Mike Mahoney.
And I was a member of that.
And I don't remember now who the other
two or three members were.
Maybe Bill Shevlin, I believe, was one of them, too.
And I must say, however, that again, Mike Mahoney did the bulk of the work on that.
And Bill Shevlin, because of his experience in teaching planning and having been on a planning faculty, I'm sure made more contributions than I did.
My experience in teaching planning
had gone back to being an adjunct and a visiting lecturer at some 20 universities, in fact, starting with University of Arkansas when I first went to Tulsa.
But anyways, the point was that Mike and I had become associated at Texas Christian University when he was on the adjunct faculty there, and he invited me to join them in about 68.
And so some of my work of that type also supported my going into educational work as a third career, as it were.
And the initial outline of the curriculum for the school was at least proposed by Professional Planning Society.
It's February 23rd, and the next interview is with Mike Mahoney.
